    "body": "@holiman \r\nI use geth geth-linux-amd64-1.7.3 in Centos 7.2 64.\r\n\r\nI found the reason and thought that this is possibly a bug of geth: **this problem is related to the path**\r\n\r\nMy directory structure of the geth is as follows:\r\n```\r\ngeth-linux-amd64-1.7.3/\r\n    -- geth\r\n    -- my-gensis.json\r\n    -- node-1/\r\n        -- data\r\n```\r\n Firstly, initialized successfully as follows:\r\n`./geth init my-gensis.json --datadir ./node-1/data`\r\n\r\nWhen I started the geth in the geth-linux-amd64-1.7.3 folder as follows:\r\n```\r\ncd geth-linux-amd64-1.7.3\r\n./geth --rpc  --datadir ./node-1/data  --rpcapi eth,miner,net,web3  --networkid 15125 console\r\n```\r\nThe problem I described before occurred: It connected to chainId 1.\r\n\r\nBut when I entered into node-1 folder and start the geth as follows:\r\n```\r\ncd geth-linux-amd64-1.7.3/node-1\r\n../geth --rpc  --datadir ./data  --rpcapi db,eth,miner,net,web3  --networkid 15125 console\r\n```\r\nIt worked fine!\r\n\r\nOn the other hand, I found that there must be a subdirectory such as data under the node-1. If the structure is as follows:\r\n```\r\ngeth-linux-amd64-1.7.3/\r\n    -- geth\r\n    -- my-gensis.json\r\n    -- node-1/\r\n```\r\nit doesn't work(always connect to chainId 1) no matter where you start the geth.\r\n\r\nI don't know if this is a bug, but it is very weird for me.\r\n\r\n\r\n",
